g.text: Exercise 3: Data Cleaning
In this exercise you explore data, check the data for outliers, and handle missing values.
Explore the properties of the data in the
interactive Data Explorer view
Replace numeric outliers in the "Age"
column, i.e the values outside the whiskers
of a boxplot, by missing values
Handle missing values
If the age of a customer is missing, replace the birthday with a missing
value (Rule Engine node)
Hint: Use the expression NOT MISSING $Age$=> $Birthday$
Impute the missing values in the age column with the column mean
Remove duplicates in the customer data
Create the lookup table to correct spelling mistakes manually
Calculate the number of occurrences by country (Value Counter node)
Extract the country name information from the RowID into a new column (RowID node)
Split the table based on the number of occurrences of the country names (<30 and >=30) (Row Splitter node)
In the table with the misspelling candidates, generate a constant value (an empty string for now) column called "Correct Country" (Constant Value
Column node)
Correct the names of the misspelled countries by typing the correct names in the "Correct Country" column in the Table Editor view (Table Editor
node)
Replace the misspelled country names in the customer information table (Cell Replacer node)
(optional): Create the lookup table to correct spelling mistakes automatically
Generate a numeric ID for each country in the lookup table (Counter Generation).
Search for the most similar country for each misspelling candidate (Similarity Search). Output the numeric ID. (Similarity Search node)
Join the similarity search output with the correct country names based on the numeric ID.
Replace the misspelled country names in the customer information table

coming from
two systems
